0At%20Some%20Point%20In%20Its%20Past%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cp%3EMars%20may%20have%20seen%20dry%20and%20wet%20season%20cycles%20and%20thus%2C%20may%20have%20been%20habitable%20at%20some%20point%20in%20its%20past%2C%20according%20to%20scientists.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAnalysis%20of%20mud%20crack%20patterns%20on%20early%20Martian%20surface%2C%20observed%20by%20NASA's%20Curiosity%20Rover%2C%20suggest%20an%20irregular%20or%20episodic%20presence%20of%20water%2C%20meaning%20water%20could%20have%20been%20present%20for%20a%20time%20and%20then%20evaporated.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20process%20may%20have%20repeated%20until%20mud%20cracks%20formed%2C%20the%20scientists%20from%20France%2C%20US%20and%20Canada%20said%20in%20their%20study.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThese%20exciting%20observations%20of%20mature%20mud%20cracks%20are%20allowing%20us%20to%20fill%20in%20some%20of%20the%20missing%20history%20of%20water%20on%20Mars.%20How%20did%20Mars%20go%20from%20a%20warm%2C%20wet%20planet%20to%20the%20cold%2C%20dry%20place%20we%20know%20today%3F%20%26quot%3BThese%20mud%20cracks%20show%20us%20that%20transitional%20time%2C%20when%20liquid%20water%20was%20less%20abundant%20but%20still%20active%20on%20the%20Martian%20surface%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Nina%20Lanza%2C%20principal%20investigator%20of%20the%20ChemCam%20instrument%20onboard%20the%20Curiosity%20Rover%20and%20one%20of%20this%20study's%20authors.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EOn%20Earth%2C%20mud%20cracks%20are%20known%20to%20assume%20a%20T-shape%20initially.%20However%2C%20subsequent%20wetting%20and%20drying%20cycles%20can%20cause%20these%20cracks%20to%20take%20more%20of%20a%20Y-shape.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Y-shape%20of%20the%20mud%20cracks%20on%20the%20Martian%20surface%2C%20therefore%2C%20could%20mean%20that%20the%20red%20planet%20saw%20wet-dry%20cycles%2C%20the%20scientists%20said%20in%20the%20study%20published%20in%20the%20journal%20Nature.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFurther%2C%20these%20cracks%20were%20only%20a%20few%20centimetres%20deep%2C%20suggesting%20that%20these%20wet-dry%20cycles%20could%20have%20been%20seasonal%20or%20could%20have%20occurred%20more%20quickly%2C%20such%20as%20through%20flash%20floods%2C%20they%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThese%20findings%2C%20thus%2C%20point%20to%20the%20possibility%20of%20Mars%20once%20having%20had%20Earth-like%20wet%20climate%20and%20that%20Mars%20may%20have%20been%20able%20to%20support%20life%20at%20some%20point.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3B(The%20wet-dry%20cycles%20create)%20the%20perfect%20place%20for%20the%20formation%20of%20polymeric%20molecules%20required%20for%20life%2C%20including%20proteins%20and%20RNA%2C%20if%20the%20right%20organic%20molecules%20were%20present%20at%20this%20location%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Patrick%20Gasda%2C%20co-author%20of%20the%20paper.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWet%20periods%20bring%20molecules%20together%20while%20dry%20periods%20drive%20reactions%20to%20form%20polymers.%20When%20these%20processes%20occur%20repeatedly%20at%20the%20same%20location%2C%20the%20chance%20increases%20that%20more%20complex%20molecules%20formed%20there%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Gasda.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThese%20features%20point%20to%20the%20existence%20of%20wet-dry%20environments%20that%20on%20Earth%20are%20extremely%20conducive%20to%20the%20development%20of%20organic%20molecules%20and%20potentially%20life.%20Taken%20as%20a%20whole%2C%20these%20results%20give%20us%20a%20clearer%20picture%20of%20Mars%20as%20a%20habitable%20world%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Lanza.%3Cbr%3E%5Cn%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ci%3E(Except%20for%20the%20headline%2C%20this%20story%20has%20not%20been%20edited%20by%20NDTV%20staff%20and%20is%20published%20from%20a%20syndicated%20feed.)%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1691666220000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fc.ndtvimg.com%2Fcuriosity-rover-nasa_625x300_1528433393580.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ndtv.com%2Fscience%2Fmars-may-have-been-habitable-at-some-point-scientists-study-nasa-rover-findin